done-so-far: Root-caused. NOT a :: bug. examples/algebraic-effects.ssc Logger handler does `msg :: resume(())` expecting resume(()) to be Nil (deep-handler accumulation). But resume(()) returns the continuation's PURE result = () (Unit), so `msg :: ()` -> "No method '::' on StringV". The spec (algebraic-effects.md:256) implies resume returns the handler-body type (List), which needs a RETURN CLAUSE (return x => Nil) to bridge the base case; ScalaScript handle has no return clause (spec's own Logger example just does resume(()) returning Unit). So the example uses an unsupported pattern. Implementing return clauses = large feature (out of scope).
